<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: &quot;Globtops&quot;?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10630&amp;p=120078#p120078"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Punch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Hi, I was looking for a donor cart to solder a rom socket so I could test my NROM games... I looked inside a pirate fami cartridge, and since I saw a package-like chip, I opened the cart. It's a pretty board for what I can tell, since there's a 6264LD + PAL16L8ACN (pirated mapper?) plus a 3V Panasonic CR2032 battery (SRAM?!?)<br /></div> Yes, the 6264LD is the battery-backed memory. No idea why they're using a PAL; what game is it? <br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />... however there was no ROM to be found except for these stupid globtops (three). Interestingly enough there's a circuit line near the center globtop marked &quot;VCR7&quot;... is that what I think it is?<br /></div>Text, especially in pirate games, likes to lie. I would not assume it's a VRC7; that functionality wouldn't fit in an PAL16 anyway.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />So anyway, my question is: is it possible to do something with this cart to accept an EPROM? Is there a way to melt this globtops away?<br /></div>Removing the gloptops isn't hard (<a href="http://www.kevtris.org/Projects/votraxpss/unpot.html" class="postlink">kevtris explains</a>), but soldering a new ROM is going to be a Serious Endeavor, involving lots of rewiring and surface-mount work. I would look for something else, or buy one of INL's kits.<br /><div class="quotetitle">Punch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />another quick question to reuse this thread: if I buy a PAL NES game, can I solder a ROM with a program made for US NES consoles and use it normally or is the pinout different?<br /></div>The pinout's the same; the pinout of DIP ROMs used in games made by Everyone but Nintendo <em>or</em> 64 KiB and smaller are standardized and trivially replaceable. That said, although NTSC games usually work on a PAL NES, the music may sound terrible (out of tune).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3512">lidnariq</a> — Wed Oct 30, 2013 10:27 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
